rComments: It was clearly the most useful IR class,ineresting. She tries to raise the level of attention with jokes and with her Maryl Streep - like behaviour. LOTS OF READINGS, but they are not too critical, just helping to deepen our knowledge. Huge essays though and obviously they always try to average around 70. Finals/ Midterms were the same like before.

This professor is really approachable and welcoming. She is also very passionate about the subject. However, her voice is really monotone and makes you fall a sleep. I really could not help it but TRN250 was my least favourite class. The course is all over the place . Lecture notes (5-8 pages per class). About 200 pages per class in readings
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Get ready to read', 'Lecture heavy']

rComments: I took TRN250  this past year and it was by far my favourite class.  Prof. MacDonald is truly caring, intelligent, and engaging. The material of the course is fascinating - history based and an unique approach to looking at IR. This course completely changed how I look at IR, history, and the world. Cannot recommend TRN250 & Prof. Macdonald enough!

I had the pleasure of being in Professor MacDonald's TRN250 class as well as TRN411. Although the content of 250 wasn't the most interesting, Professor MacDonald was nothing but an engaging, enthusiastic and inspirational educator. She is one of the kindest professors I've had, and is VERY flexible in letting students pursue their interests.

Professor MacDonald is such a lovely person! She makes herself available to you and is always willing to give you advice and feedback. The course itself was pretty dry, but she did her best to make it interesting. She makes you think deeper.

Lovely professor that's passionate about her job, and motivates her students to explore their curiosities. However, I was not a fan of the inverted classroom style of learning. Her online modules were well structured, however the Q&A period (1st hr) was so boring. Skip the first hour and just go to tutorial. But still watch modules!!!

The inverted classroom is the main beef with my experience of the professor. It leads to a classroom experience where the first hour of class is steeped in awkward silence and boredom. I'm sure the professor is wonderful teaching using other methods, but this experience is what sours me on her so far.

TRN250 uses the concept of an inverted class room. Lectures are online modules and there is a weekly seminar -style discussion. Very enjoyable material, focuses on norms such as sovereignty, humanitarian intervention and free trade. Lots of reading, but interesting. Great mock G20 session (taken for credit!). Prof is very approachable and helpful.
